author: El Día
title: UD TENERIFE: Sandra Castelló firma un retorno con victoria
text:
Hasta la décima fecha liguera había sido imprescindible para Eder Maestre. Sandra Castelló, fichada este verano por el Costa Adeje, se hizo un hueco desde el primer momento en el centro del campo de las guerreras, y acumuló diez titularidades en otros tantos compromisos de Liga F. Sin embargo, una rotura fibrilar le hizo perderse los últimos cuatro duelos de 2024 y retornó el pasado fin de semana al césped , donde ejerció de pulmón para las suyas.
«Me he sentido muy cómoda. Tenía ganas de volver y de incorporarme al equipo, intentando aportar todo lo que pueda», señala la alicantina tras ser de la partida en la victoria del equipo azul y blanco ante el Depor Abanca. « Me he adaptado bastante rápido gracias al grupo que tienen desde años anteriores y eso ha facilitado mi incorporación», afirma.
Algo a lo que también ha contribuido su propio nivel, siendo una de las jugadoras con mayor número de balones recuperados. Pese a ello, Caste pone el foco en el grupo, dado que su trabajo es aportar «todo lo que pueda al equipo, ir a por el partido, sumar los tres puntos y estar siempre disponible».
La siguiente oportunidad será el choque de este sábado en Granada, un partido que «será muy disputado». « Sabemos la importancia que tiene sumar fuera , así que iremos a por el partido buscando la victoria y cerrar la primera vuelta en buena posición», concluye.

author: María Martín Balmaseda
title: Fin de semana marcado por mucho frío, lluvia y nieve en Castilla-La Mancha: estos son los puntos más afectados según la AEMET
text:
Fin de semana marcado por mucho frío, lluvia y nieve en Castilla-La Mancha: estos son los puntos más afectados según la AEMET
Se registrarán mínimas bajo 0, además de heladas y lluvias en diferentes zonas de la Comunidad Autónoma.
El próximo 21 de diciembre arranca de manera oficial el invierno en España. Una estación que ya se está haciendo notar en Castilla-La Mancha desde que el pasado lunes la
[Agencia Estatal de Meteorología (AEMET)](https://www.larazon.es/castilla-la-mancha/ultima-hora-aemet-heladas-debiles-minimas-cero-zonas-castilla-mancha/20241211/1141275.html)alertó de la llegada de una nueva borrasca denominada 'Darragh' que traería consigo un temporal de nieve, lluvia y viento, además de un notable descenso de las temperaturas en gran parte de la Península Ibérica.Con todo ello, este viernes se esperan brumas y bancos de niebla matinales dispersos en diferentes zonas de Castilla-La Mancha, especialmente en el este de Albacete, Cuenca y Guadalajara. Sin embargo, las provincias de Toledo y Ciudad Real y el sur de Cuenca se verán afectadas por la llegadas de tormentas y chubascos escasos que irán disminuyendo a lo largo del día. Con respecto a la cota de nieve permanecerá ente 1.200 - 1.400 metros y en el sureste entre 1400 - 1600.
Con respecto a las temperaturas mínimas, estas ascenderán moderadamente hasta los 3 grados en Cuenca y Toledo, hasta los 2 en Ciudad Real y hasta los 0 en Albacete; mientras que en Guadalajara serán de -1 grado. Por otro lado, las máximas sufrirán pocos cambios con respecto al jueves, situándose entre los 9 y 13 grados. Durante la jornada también se prevén heladas débiles en los Sistemas Central e Ibérico y zonas aledañas, y moderadas en cumbres.
Mínimas bajo 0 y lluvias
El fin de semana arrancará el sábado con posibles brumas y nieblas matinales en amplias zonas de Guadalajara y más dispersas en los valles del Tajo y del Guadiana, así como en puntos de La Mancha. Se alcanzarán mínimas bajo cero el sábado en casi toda la comunidad, excepto en Toledo donde serán de 1ºC.
Al igual que el viernes, las heladas débiles generalizadas continuarán y seguirán siendo moderadas en el cuadrante noreste. En cuanto a las máximas, continuarán en 10 grados en Cuenca y Guadalajara, 11 en Ciudad Real y 12 en Toledo y Albacete.
La jornada del domingo estará marcada por cielos poco nubosos o despejados. Las temperaturas mínimas aumentarán ligeramente en el nordeste, alcanzando los 0 grados en Guadalajara y Toledo, -1ºC en Ciudad Real y -2ºC en Cuenca y Albacete.
Las máximas subirán hasta los 12 grados en Toledo y Albacete, hasta los 11 en Guadalajara y Ciudad Real, y hasta los 10 en Cuenca. Tampoco se descarta alguna precipitación débil y aislada en la Mancha occidental de madrugada.
Termómetros con hasta -2ºC
Para la próxima semana, se prevé que se mantenga una situación anticiclónica en la Península y Baleares, principalmente durante la jornada del lunes y el martes, en las que predominarán los cielos poco nubosos o los intervalos de nubes altas.
De igual modo, se registrará un descenso generalizado de las temperaturas mínimas y los termómetros marcarán hasta -2ºC en toda la región castellano-manchega, a excepción de Ciudad Real, que se situará en -1ºC. Por el contrario, las máximas no variarán con respecto al domingo.

author: Carrol Strain
title: The Role of Employee Training in Preventing Business Theft
text:
Featured image by
jefftakespics2
In the landscape of modern business, theft extends beyond the physical, encompassing technology, equipment, and even intellectual property. It’s a challenge that necessitates a vigilant and well-informed workforce.
Equipping employees with the right knowledge and skills not only protects a business against various theft risks but also cultivates an environment of proactive security. As theft tactics overall become more sophisticated, the role of employee training in safeguarding a company’s diverse assets becomes increasingly vital.
Understanding Business Theft: A Broad Perspective
Business theft is an all-encompassing term that spans from the swiping of office supplies to the sophisticated cyber theft of sensitive data. It’s not just about the immediate loss of physical items. It is also about the ramifications that can ripple through a business, affecting everything from morale to the bottom line.
Recognizing the varied faces of business theft is the first step in crafting an effective defense strategy. This understanding is crucial in training employees to identify and prevent potential thefts, thus making them an integral part of the company’s security apparatus.
Theft of Technology: Guarding Digital Business Assets
In the digital age, technology theft has emerged as a major concern for almost every business. From laptops to proprietary software, the spectrum of technological assets vulnerable to theft is broad. Therefore, training employees to secure these digital assets goes beyond simple password protection. It involves instilling a culture of overall cybersecurity awareness.
RELATED ARTICLE:
TAKE STEPS TO PROTECT YOUR BUSINESS FROM CYBERCRIME
Whether it’s recognizing phishing attempts or following strict data access protocols, employees’ vigilance plays a critical role. As technology becomes increasingly integral to business operations, equipping staff with the knowledge to protect digital assets is not just a precaution. It’s a necessity for safeguarding the heart of modern business.
RELATED ARTICLE:
WHAT IS AN HTML SMUGGLING ATTACK?
Securing Physical Equipment: From Office Supplies to Machinery
Securing physical equipment, from office essentials to large machinery, is a fundamental aspect of security for your business. The risk posed by theft of these items can significantly disrupt business operations. Beyond basic measures like locking doors, effective employee training should foster a collective sense of responsibility and heightened awareness. Employees need to be adept at recognizing suspicious activities as well as fluent in reporting procedures.
Regular audits and explicit guidelines on equipment usage and storage are also crucial. Involving staff in safeguarding physical assets not only enhances security but also cultivates a more conscientious workplace. This is crucial for the protection of a business’s tangible investments.
Fuel Theft: A Growing Concern for Businesses
In the face of rising fuel prices and its increasing value, businesses are recognizing the importance of
preventing fuel theft. Training employees in vigilant monitoring of fuel storage and awareness of theft indicators is essential. Discussing the benefits of steel bunded tanks, which offer robust security with their dual-layered structure, forms a key part of this training.
Equally important is familiarizing staff with fuel management systems that can track consumption and signal any unusual activity. By integrating these strategies, employees become proactive in protecting this essential asset, thus fortifying the business against potential fuel theft.
Preventing Intellectual Property Theft: Safeguarding Business Ideas
Intellectual property theft, often overlooked, can be as damaging as the theft of physical assets. It involves the unauthorized use of ideas, inventions, or creative expressions, which are the lifeblood of many businesses. Training employees about the importance of IP rights, proper handling of sensitive information, and adherence to non-disclosure agreements is crucial.
By instilling a culture that respects and protects intellectual property, businesses not only secure their innovative ideas but also foster an environment of trust and integrity. This approach ensures that the intellectual assets, the drivers of growth and competitive advantage, are well-guarded.
Enhancing Business Security with Effective Monitoring Systems
Utilizing modern monitoring systems like CCTV and resource management tools is key to enhancing business security.
CCTV cameras work to significantly prevent crime, providing continuous visual monitoring, acting as a deterrent to theft and recording evidence if an incident occurs.
Resource management systems help track the use and inventory of assets, quickly identifying any unusual patterns that might suggest theft. These systems are straightforward yet powerful tools in a business’s security strategy. They offer an extra layer of protection, helping businesses keep a closer eye on their assets and respond quickly to any security threats.

author: Michael Errigo
title: Paul VI girls close out tough month with ‘fun’ in win over Visitation - The Washington Post
text: December has been a hard month for the Paul VI girls’ basketball team. A consistent power in the Washington Catholic Athletic Conference, the Panthers often spend the early weeks of the season navigating an arduous nonconference slate. This month was no different; Paul VI jumped from one national event to the other, playing teams from Alabama, California, Florida and New York. But the No. 8 Panthers struggled to keep up with the competition — their youth and injury woes holding them back against the country’s elite. The team also was playing without Coach Scott Allen, who missed the first five weeks of the season as he dealt with the death of his mother. Thursday afternoon’s game against No. 9 Georgetown Visitation in Northwest Washington was Allen’s first one back, and he watched with pride as his team set a more optimistic tone for 2024. The Panthers played a smart, physical game, topping the Cubs, 53-47. “I’ve been doing this for 28 years, and I’ve learned this is supposed to be fun,” Allen said. “You try to keep that perspective. So I told the team after the game, ‘I had fun today.’ Life can be hard, so the opportunity to be back in the gym with these guys is something I’m so thankful for.” Panthers forward Laura Williams, the team’s lone senior, scored 34 of her team’s 53 points. Williams, an athletic 6-foot-3 playmaker, generated one close-range look after another and finished with 15 two-point field goals. “This team has definitely had its ups and downs [since] the beginning of this season,” Williams said. “But I know this group, and I know we’re going to be okay. We’ve had other seasons start slow, and we’re just looking for our groove.” This game opened the D.C. Holiday Hoopla, a two-day showcase event hosted by St. John’s. It is one of many basketball events being held across the region this week, as local programs capitalize on the time off from school between Christmas and New Year’s. The matchup was mostly shaped by which team could better execute a full-court press. In the first half, it was the Panthers (4-7) who applied relentless pressure and built a double-digit lead. The lead disappeared in the third quarter as Visitation (5-5) went to its own press and seized momentum. Visitation senior Toby Nweke sank two free throws to cut the Panthers’ lead to one with one minute remaining in the quarter. That was the closest Visitation would get as Paul VI responded with six quick points. Junior Hazel Grepps scored back-to-back baskets, the second of which came with an opportunity for a three-point play. Grepps missed the ensuing free throw, but Williams scored on a putback as the period ended. The Panthers entered the fourth with a seven-point lead and a renewed sense of control. “Every one of these young players is trying to earn their spot every minute, so I try to tell them to relax,” Williams said. “I don’t ever want to get mad at mistakes. We just get mad at a lack of effort or nonchalance. I just tell them to have fun, and today was fun.”

I’m simply aiming to lower this failure rate and achieve something positive in the process.”VICTORVILLE, CALIFORNIA, UNITED STATES, January 7, 2024 / — Norman Szobotka | Real Estate Agent, Founder of Realtors Vacuum [EINPresswire.com](https://www.einpresswire.com/)/ -- In the dynamic world of real estate, where success is often elusive, [Norman Szobotka](https://www.normanszobotka.com/?utm_source=pr)stands as a guiding influence and a source of inspiration. At the age of 26, this seasoned real estate agent and founder of [Realtors Vacuum](https://www.realtorschoose.com/?utm_source=pr)has not only disrupted the industry but has also played a pivotal role in decreasing the failure rate among real estate agents. His journey began with a vision to empower his peers with the tools they need to thrive. Through his top-tier real estate data company, he identified a unique opportunity to elevate the success of his fellow agents by focusing on this industry’s hidden gems — high-equity homeowners and renters with impressive credit scores. By providing a specialized platform that enables agents to target this high-potential market segment, this company has single-handedly revolutionized the industry’s approach. The heart of his mission lies not just in business success but in making a positive impact on the community. Realtors Vacuum operates on a cause-based marketing model, ensuring that with every successful transaction closed by their clients, a contribution is made to support the homeless community. His company believes that success should be a catalyst for positive change, and his commitment to social responsibility is reshaping the real estate landscape. This company has become a catalyst for change, not only in the lives of real estate agents but also in the broader community. Szobotka’s vision goes beyond profit margins; it’s about creating a ripple effect of prosperity and compassion. As real estate professionals find success, they are simultaneously contributing to a cause that addresses homelessness, making every transaction a step towards a better future for those in need. His journey speaks volumes beyond business expertise; it's a testament to the transformative potential when innovation, purpose, and social responsibility intertwine. Through his unwavering commitment, he has not only decreased the industry’s failure rate but has also sown the seeds of positive change that will continue to flourish for years to come.
